hands_on_practices.solution:
Our goal is to derive the explicit form of the endomorphism $\mathcal{R}_k$ in the Weitzenböck identity $\Delta \omega = 
abla^{*} 
abla \omega + \mathcal{R}_{k} \omega$. To achieve this, we will express the Hodge Laplacian $\Delta = d\delta + \delta d$ in terms of the connection Laplacian $
abla^*
abla$ and curvature terms. The derivation is most transparent when performed at an arbitrary point $p \in M$ using a local orthonormal frame $\{e_{1}, \dots, e_{n}\}$ that forms a normal coordinate system centered at $p$. In such a frame, at the point $p$, we have $g(e_i, e_j)|_p = \delta_{ij}$ and $(
abla_{e_i} e_j)|_p = 0$. Since the Levi-Civita connection is torsion-free, its torsion tensor $T(X,Y) = 
abla_X Y - 
abla_Y X - [X,Y]$ vanishes. At the point $p$, this implies $[e_i, e_j]|_p = (
abla_{e_i} e_j)|_p - (
abla_{e_j} e_i)|_p = 0$.

Let $\omega$ be a differential $k$-form. In a local orthonormal frame, the exterior derivative $d$ and its adjoint, the codifferential $\delta$, can be expressed using the Levi-Civita connection $
abla$ as:
$$
d\omega = \sum_{i=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge 
abla_{e_{i}} \omega
$$
$$
\delta\omega = -\sum_{j=1}^{n} i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega
$$
where $\{e^i\}$ is the dual coframe, $i_{e_j}$ is the interior product with $e_j$, and $\wedge$ is the wedge product.

First, we compute the term $\delta d\omega$:
$$
\delta d\omega = -\sum_{i=1}^{n} i_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{i}} (d\omega) = -\sum_{i=1}^{n} i_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{i}} \left(\sum_{j=1}^{n} e^{j} \wedge 
abla_{e_{j}} \omegaight)
$$
Using the product rule for $
abla$, we get:
$$
\delta d\omega = -\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} i_{e_{i}} \left( (
abla_{e_{i}} e^{j}) \wedge 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega + e^{j} \wedge 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega ight)
$$
At the point $p$, our choice of a normal frame ensures $(
abla_{e_i} e^j)|_p = 0$. Thus, at $p$:
$$
\delta d\omega = -\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} i_{e_{i}} (e^{j} \wedge 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega)
$$
We use the algebraic identity for interior product and wedge product: $i_{X}(\alpha \wedge  eta) = (i_{X}\alpha) eta - \alpha \wedge (i_{X} eta)$ for a $1$-form $\alpha$. Here $i_{e_i}e^j = e^j(e_i) = \delta_{i}^{j}$.
$$
\delta d\omega = -\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} \left(\delta_{i}^{j} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega - e^{j} \wedge i_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omegaight)
$$
Summing over $i$ using the Kronecker delta $\delta_i^j$:
$$
\delta d\omega = -\sum_{j=1}^{n} 
abla_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega + \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{j} \wedge i_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega
$$
The connection Laplacian $
abla^{*}
abla$ is defined as the trace of the second covariant derivative, which in a normal frame at $p$ is $
abla^{*}
abla\omega = -\sum_{j=1}^{n} 
abla_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega$. Therefore:
$$
\delta d\omega = 
abla^{*}
abla\omega + \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{j} \wedge i_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega
$$

Next, we compute the term $d\delta\omega$:
$$
d\delta\omega = \sum_{i=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge 
abla_{e_{i}} (\delta\omega) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge 
abla_{e_{i}} \left(-\sum_{j=1}^{n} i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omegaight) = -\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge 
abla_{e_{i}}(i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega)
$$
The commutator of the covariant derivative and the interior product is given by $[
abla_{X}, i_{Y}] = i_{
abla_{X}Y}$. At our point $p$, $(
abla_{e_{i}}e_{j})|_p = 0$, so $[
abla_{e_{i}}, i_{e_{j}}]|_p = 0$. The operators commute at $p$.
$$
d\delta\omega = -\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega
$$

Now we combine these results to form the Hodge Laplacian $\Delta\omega = d\delta\omega + \delta d\omega$:
$$
\Delta\omega = \left(
abla^{*}
abla\omega + \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{j} \wedge i_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omegaight) - \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega
$$
Let us analyze the curvature part, which is the sum of the last two terms. We can swap the dummy summation indices $i$ and $j$ in the first sum:
$$
\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{j} \wedge i_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega = \sum_{j,i=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} \omega
$$
Substituting this back into the expression for $\Delta\omega$:
$$
\Delta\omega = 
abla^{*}
abla\omega + \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} \omega - \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega
$$
Factoring out the common operators:
$$
\Delta\omega = 
abla^{*}
abla\omega + \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} \left(
abla_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} \omega - 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omegaight)
$$
We now use the definition of the curvature endomorphism on the bundle of $k$-forms, $R^{\Lambda^{k}}(X,Y) \omega = 
abla_{X} 
abla_{Y} \omega - 
abla_{Y} 
abla_{X} \omega - 
abla_{[X,Y]} \omega$. At the point $p$, we have $[e_i, e_j]|_p = 0$, so $R^{\Lambda^{k}}_{e_{i}, e_{j}}\omega := R^{\Lambda^{k}}(e_{i}, e_{j})\omega = 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega - 
abla_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} \omega$. Therefore, $
abla_{e_{j}} 
abla_{e_{i}} \omega - 
abla_{e_{i}} 
abla_{e_{j}} \omega = -R^{\Lambda^{k}}_{e_{i}, e_{j}}\omega$.
Substituting this into our expression for $\Delta\omega$:
$$
\Delta\omega = 
abla^{*}
abla\omega - \sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} \left(R^{\Lambda^{k}}_{e_{i}, e_{j}}\omegaight)
$$
By comparing this with the given Weitzenböck identity, $\Delta \omega = 
abla^{*} 
abla \omega + \mathcal{R}_{k} \omega$, we identify the action of the curvature operator $\mathcal{R}_k$ on $\omega$:
$$
\mathcal{R}_{k}\omega = -\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} R^{\Lambda^{k}}_{e_{i}, e_{j}}\omega
$$
Since this holds for any $k$-form $\omega$, the operator $\mathcal{R}_k$ itself is given by the expression:
$$
\mathcal{R}_{k} = -\sum_{i,j=1}^{n} e^{i} \wedge i_{e_{j}} R^{\Lambda^{k}}_{e_{i}, e_{j}}
$$
This is a tensorial expression derived at a special point in a special frame, but by the principle of covariance, it holds globally in any frame. This expression depends only on the wedge product, interior product, and the curvature endomorphisms as required.
